nmental to his character in connec-\n'ion with the rxp'oit.\n\"If Ueut. Farreli thinks that any-\nthim: has been said injurious to his\nv.-r utation as an olfioer ho can pro-\ni sent it to this rourt,\"\nanlels\n:rmlied. \"If I lind that this court\nE;has not the power to vindicate him\ni in the event that he sustains his\nj contentions, a special court can be\nj convened for that purpose.\"\nI The naval secretary earlier in the\no.av had \"deplored\" the clash be-\ni. vn Ijieuts. Farreli and Hinton.\nz-'AT'oman Thrown to Street\nWhen Street Car Starts\nMrs. Anna Heyye, 137 Unden\nav.. was seriously lnjureq eanes\ni day night when she attempted t\n'get off a Chapin st. car nt Main st.\nand Washington nv. The car is al\nleged to have startetl brfore Mrs.\nO iroii in iiavo M.arieu oi ior' -irs.\nHoyse had alighted, throwing her n\nho inv-;iio' and injuring her right\nhip and elbow.\nTho pdir. ambulance was called\nand she was remox'ed to her home.\nThe po'.'co were told\nir t- tot.l till t fhi In-\nj Jurcd vortati\ntirtod to leavo\nthe l\ncar r-awar-is\n.started before\nui or.r. she was\nthe street.\nr. nd when the\n\nshe reached the\nthrown foreiblv to\nGilmer Sentences Tico\nFor Dry Laic Violations\nI\nj .lud go Crmer showed no mercy to\nv-ol.Kors of the liquor laws nr\n\"raisned in the citv court Wedr.es-\nday and senteed two of them\nfound truilty to terms In the coun'y\n.\"ail and on tho penal form and fined\n..1-.V. .sff.: f 1 Hfl nnil rAc'c li?il\nm I'.k-.i I'll, in' I V v.\nSihi who was arrested bx- Ser\"t.\nBob. riu and a detail of oihcers on a\nraid on his place on the west tide,\nand Mike Hobar. at whose hom two\ns ills were found, were tho men\nfound guilty and sentenced by tho\njudge.\nU CW To taf\nA Regular Baby;\nWho Wants Her?\nh dot-sn't know it in fact sh\nisn't intf-restrd in anything much ex\ncept a coa pie of eluwive pink toeH\nand a bottle that -won't stay put\nbut there is a younp lady down at\nthe Salvation Army station who i-making-\na hig- apnal to the hearts\nof\nSouth Itend mothers. She wants\nhome with someone.\nThe your. ir mother brought the\nI bany, only It. days old. to Capt.\nI i-vltt nt\nnt the station Wednesday,\nung mai ne nnii n. nom ffr h'r\nCapt. Trevitt came to Th 'ews-\nTimes.\nThe mothor hprlf nnsMn tn\nemployment, will po to the Salva-\ntion Army's institution in Chicago or\nDetroit. Now Capt. Trevitt Ls wait-\niing for someone to\noffer the baby\na home. Yoti ran\nphone him at\nMain 1.-502.\nBLAMES MODERN\nMODE OF LIVING\nFOR CRIME YAYE\n\"Movies\" Shown in South\nBend Openly Immoral,\nSays Minister.\n\"We cannot blame the present\nunrent of the world upon agitators\nand I teds, but upon ourselves. Tho\ngreat wave of crime that is sweeping\nthe country today nvay be traced iu\nlarge part to us who live In cities\nand. towns, as good citizens of the\nland, and this because of mode of\nthought and action and manner of\nfullilling the mission of our lives.\nI Great and growing challenges have\ni arisen from the age and we have\nu.o-,f,,p,, tn tv, ,w\nf -i 1 bn\nintr lha ritte rf\nm-;\" ewhlnp foi\nline of least resistance, instead of\nrising up and facing the evils before\nus.\"\nThese were the words of Rev.\nAlbert E. Monger, pastor oof the\nFirst M. K. church, in the course of\nhis address at thu Church Family\nNight supper and meeting Wednes\nday owning in the banquet hall of\nthe church. Supper was followed by\ncongregational singing, ltd by Col.\nI v m mi 1 1 ft ii 11 il-\nlnt.rl. ,)u.:,ioitM.\nI world expected a spiritual\nuplift after the war\" Haid the speak\ner. \"We anticipated a great moral\nelevation in the thoughts and deeds\ndisappointed\n1\nj Lilteriy\nso. Kven here in our\njf hJ c prevalent as much\ni as u vXvr wasJ bt,foie and there\nte be no reined). So will it always\nbe while we turn away our heads\n,and hold indifferent ears to the noise\nI of the evils about us.\n\"Instead of standing forth and\nfacing this state of things we live\non in our diilident way of thinking\nand doting on the little and trivial\nthings of life until they have become\nthe big things in it .and thus our houIs\nare become wurped and puny, our\ni ideals tarnished .and our sense of\nservice to othcr.n lost form our vision.\nWe all remember Cabel andjoshua\nfrom the Rible and think of them,\nmore than we do of the other ten\ntribe leaders, because they had a\nsense of service and desired to be\ncontinually doing sreatt things.\nCabel said when he was four score\nand live years old, to hin masters\nwhen they were contemplating the\nland ot pleasant valleys and of milk\nand honey: \"Give me the hill\ncountry.\" for he wanted to po out\nfrom common ways and be a. poineer\namong men.\nIn- Tlirimnd T !Vi\na;.., Ulli\n.\"That is what we need in our hearts\ni today, the slogan of Cabel, \"Give\nme the hill country.\" We have fallen\ninto tho ruts of life and we pursue\nthe even tenor of our days without\na thought of serice or of doing\nsomething good for others. We've\nbeen 'jazzing our way through life.'\ncontent to let our minds rest upon\nour own little affairs and let the\nrest of tho world go hang.\n\"We m.unt meet the challenge of\nlawlessness a:\nWe must ta\nand that of miseducation.\nke pains to have our\nyouth iroperlv educated in the right\nmorals and principles of good living.\nIt must indeed be a terrible state of\naffairs when we can take the most\npopular and common means of\npleasure and educate the 'movie'\nand lind it rotten and corrupt beyond\nwords. The \"movie\" In itself is a\ngood and great institution but when\nit is put to such psos as many recent\nproductions have been then it is\nhigh tim to yit up and se what is\nhappening, before our eyes. A recent\npicture shown at one of the leading\nplayhouses of this eity furnishes an\nni-n nolft tn nrv'nt C-n Wo a.1..,\nj tising .van thoroughly and openly\nimmoral beyond all points of dis\ncretion or common decency. And yet\nthe crowds Hocked therj and tho\nyouth of this city were among them.\nChurch Mum JauI.\n\"This is our problem. There is\nonly one remedy, it devolves upon\nthe churches of thi.s city to lead the\nwav in opposing the evils upon us\nand In facing the challenges that\nbid fair to work harm if we sit still\n'1 anJ nothing. The ffag of Christ\nmust nut retreat herore the encroach\nments of evil. Cnder that flag will\nth people rise to their knowledge\nand faith in high ideals and prin-\nJ ciples, and under that ilag only can\nthat come about.\"\ni\nJ 1 f IV '11\nIndianapolis Man Will\nHead Vegetable Growers\nBv Associated Press:\nbFAYKTTi:. Ind.. Jan. 12. W.\nR. Myers. Indianapolis, a. named\nI presuie\nnt of the Indiana Vegetable\nassociation organized at\nPurdue university, where the veg\netable men came for the farmers'\nannual short course. Albert Morris\nof Crawf ordsville, wa named xice\npresident; H. Ib Brown. Purdue,\nsecretary, and W. S. Roebuck. Fort\nI Wayn\". treasurer. The organization\nI started with HCO members.\nj Charles A. Brown. Franklin, was\nnamed president of the Indiana\nCorn C. row ers asseciation to suc-\nteed Ij. M. VosIt. Hope, at the an\nnual meeting heid today in connec\ntion with the farmers' short course\nat Purdue university. Peter J. Lux.\nShelby ille, was named irc presi\ndent; Prof. n. I. Christie. I-afay-f'tte.\nfccorotary-treasurer. District\nvice presidents are (lien Smiley,\nRochester; C B. Moore. Scire -levlllo\nFdward Sturm. I Una; J. I. Hull.\nColumbus, and J. A. McCarty, Iv-\nERSRINE DECLARES\nU. S. BUSINESS CAN\nNOT BE KEPT DOWN\nSays American Commerct;\ni Convalescing After Ma\nis\njor Operation.\nIIV A. It. HI I SK INT..\nPn-sident StudehnUer CoriHration.\nAmerican business has boon un\nder a major operation, but i.s now\noff the operating table and back in\nth convalescent ward. Tn the lan\nguage of the street, It was \"tome\noperation.\" whi'.e In the language of\nthe doctors, the operation was pro\nnounced \"a success,\" rven though\nthe patient lived. With curtailment\nof credit, enforced liquidation, fal\nling r.rices and suspended demand,\nit w\"a indeed a sick patient for six\nmonths, but you cannot kill Ameri\ncan business, which is big enough to\nchar.go economic conditions when\nbacked with the natural resources\nof this marvelously endowed coun-\ntry.\nWith our gront crops, unlimited\nmineral resources, big merchant ma\nrine, and IGO.COO.OflO intelligent, in\ngenious people. America can and\nshould be prosperous in spite of\nworld conditions. Everybody wis\nplunging and reckless tho year and\na half following the end of the war,\nand we wore due for a tumble, but\nnow that we have had it. business\ncan settle down and prosper on the\nlower and healthier level of values\nthat have been established by liqui\ndation. Enforced liquidation and\nspeculation have, in many cases,\ndriven prices below values and costs\nof production. When such extremes\nare reached, prices rebound and\nconfidence slowly returns. What ,ve\nneed is a stabilization of prices at\nvaluation level\", especially for farm\nproducts, which are already b-?low\ncosts of production; and a return\nof confidence which will bring buy\ners back into the market.\nCan't Keep Rtiluoss Down.\nSpeaking generally, f-rices of raw\nmaterials are liquidated to a valua\ntion basis, but retail prices for some\ngoods are yet too high. This latter\nsituation will undoubtedly be clear\ned up before the winter is over, and\nwith the return of spring and sun\nshine, people will have more \"pep\"\nand enthusiasm. Our feeling of\n\"blues\" Is to a largo degree\npsychological. American business\ncannot be kept down, and will re\nbound to big volume wdth surprising\nrecovery. The Idea of from two to\nfive yenrs of continued depression\nbesettirg this country is dangerous\nto foster, repugnant and impossible,\nbecause American Industry and the\nspirit of American business will not\npermit it.\nThe gigantic industries of Amer\nica, marvelous In their ingenuity,\nability and extent, are the work\nshops of the world, .supplying not\nonly our domestic requirements of\npractically all manufactured goods,\nbut those of the world at largo to a\ndecree and extent which no other\nindustrial nation ever before achiev\ned, or can achieve against our com\npetition, because of our vastly great\ner size. This statement of fact is\nnot made boastfully or in derogation\na? the industries of other nation,\nbut simply to refute skeptical state\nments of extended depression. True,\nthe derangement of foreign ex\nchanges, with the depreciation of\nforden currencies, is an obstacle to\nAmerican exports that hampers\ntheir fullest development, but a tre\nmendous export trade will be done\nin spite of this situation. T am\ntherefore confident of the future\nprosperity of American business,\nmd consequently, of the American\npeople.\n.Auto Hnclnrs to Kmivpr.\nSponkinsr broadly, tho automobile\nbusiness will recover as quickly as\nany and remain, as heretofore, a\nconspicuous figure in American in\ndustry.. Anybody who thinks the\nautomobile business has been under\nmined Is badly mistaken. It is the\nthird largest of our Indus-tries, and\nwill prow intend of lesson in Im\nportance. Tiie strong companies of\nthe industry, with adequate phnts\nand car-ital and roorl products, will\ngrow and Increase their huslne.??.\nThose of us In the automobile busi\nness believe in tho recovery of busi\nness, the future of our industry, and\nthe return of prosperity this year.\nOFFICIALS A It I tl 'ST COUNT.\nSPOKANF. Wash., Jan. 12.\nCount and Countess Vigo Hobtein\nKathlou. of Denmark, tho latter for\nm Tly tho wife of Dr. Hoy A. Miles\njCnll.ru. killed in Portland in 1909.\niwero arrested here Wednesday ley\nUnited States immigration authori\nties and are being held for possible\nj deportation.\nMOTHER!\n\"California Syrup of Figs\"\nI Child's Best Laxative\nAccept \"California\" Syrup of Figs\nonlv look for tho name California\nIon the package, then you are sure\nj your child is having the best and\nj most harmless physic for the little\nstomach, liver and bowels. Children\nj love its fruity taste. Fu'.l directions\nion each bottle. You must say \"Cali\nIfornia.\" Adv.\nKILL THAT COLD\ni&ke hot cnpfal cf\nBULGARIAN BLOOD TEA\nIntreiM th blood circulation, fuih tb\nk!dnT. timn!t\u00c4 tfc liver, ward o5 fix\nsrirr .nd pnenmonl. Sold by dra3it\nand groctn tTerjwh!ra,\nRepublican Chairman\nVisits Capital City\nr.y Ak\"-ci it-d Pr\nINlMANAPOLl.s, ind. Jr.n. 12.\nWill Hays, chairman of the repub\nlican rational com mittet-, was greet-\nd Wedmsday ;us the next postmas-\nter general by\nwho met him\ncapitol. where\nthree mail carriers\nin the state house\n1 e called to meet\nGov. McCrav.\n\"Well, Will, wo\nby us boys.' s.iid\nping the political\nshoulder, while\ncompanions nodd\nwords. hope you do good\none carrier, slap\nleader on the\nthe spokesman's\nd assent to his\n.ur. nays ren:v was a r.on-com\nmital smile. Iater he declined to\ndiscuss possibilities of cabinet selec\ntions by Prvs't-eleet Harding.\nMr. I fays' visit in the governor's\nhamber was brit f. and he said his\nonly purpose was to congratulato\nthe new governo- upon his induc\ntion into oil ice. and to explain that\nthe press of wrok in Washington\nand N-w York kept him from at\ntending tho inauguration. Mr. llaj\nleft here Wednesday night for his\nhome in Sullivan.\nSAYS FAIR PLAY IS\nINDUSTRY'S NEED\nCapital and Labor Must Learn\nCooperation. Says\nTremaine.\n\"There has not been an industrial\ndifficulty in the United States for\nthe last years, but oould have\nbeen settled at the start fair 'lay\nwas used on both sides- by both cap\nital and labor\" said Dr. F. Tremaine\nof Cleveland. Ohio, In his address at\na meeting ot the employment mana\ngers of South Bend and Mishawaka\nindustries in the Chamber of Com\nmerce Wednesday evening.\nA. I-. Ityan of Wilson Bros,\nexplained Thrift Week plans\nspoke strongly cf cooperation\ntween the various factories of\nCo.\nand\ntwo towns.\nItyan has been appoint\ned chairman of the industrial com\nmittee by Fred Keller who is in\ncharge of the campaign in this city.\nNtKiIs Personal f.'oiich.\n\"What has happened in our in\ndustrial world within the past sev\neral years and it must be saved\nagain is th- utter lack of personal\ntouch\" said Dr. Tremaine. \"In the\ndays not so many years a uro and still\nwithin memory of men we had the\npersonal touch ir. our industries.that\nis tho workman lived closer to his\nboss and they worked together in\ntheir respective fields more as men\nwho understand and appreciate each\nother.\n\"With the growth of our indus\ntries came the beginline r,f the\ntrouble between labor and capital.\nThe personal touch between employ\ner and employee was lost. We have\nnot yet replaced it and without its\nbeing brought back in some way\nthere will be no peace in the indus\ntrial world. There are many sys\ntems of bringing it back and some\nare good :unl some otherwise but\nwhat labor and capital must first\nsee and obtain before they intend\nto try any progress in their relations\nis the spirit of fair plav.\n\"As Man to Man.\"\n\"Both sides must learn to talk to\neach other not as man to man but\nas man with man. A hand must be\nextended instead of a fist. The cards\nmust bo placed on the table for the\neyes of all to see- and everything\nopen and above board. But as yet\nwo are only groping and experiment\ning in, the -dark for we are new and\ninexperienced in the industrial ques\ntion. Consequently wo need coop\neration between the heads of factor\nies and industrial centers over tho\ncountry. We cannot work alono and\nhave each going: in a different direc\ntion. Cooperation, fair play and a\nspirit of unselfishness and helpful\nness is needed among\" all of us and\nparticularly so in the world of In\ndustry, whore labcr and capital have\nnot vet come to an understanding.\nWould Limit Trading\nIn Grain Futures by\nR roher s of America\nIly Assim dated Pres\nWASIlINt;TCN, Jan. 12. While\nrepresentatives of western grain in\nterests and exchanges were appear\ning before- the hous' agriculture\ncommitter \"Wednesday in exposition\nto proposed logislatifn to regulate\nfuture exchanges, bills were intro\nduced simultaneously in the senate\nand house limiting to 200.000 bush\nels the amount of grain whi'-h tan\nbo traded in as futures by any one\nperson and requiring delivery on fu\ntures contract of the actual grade of\ngrain specified.\nThe bills were introduce d by Sen.\nGronna, republican, North Dakota,\nand Itep. Ilaucron. republican. Iowa,\nchairmen of the respective agricul\nture committees.\nAt the hearing before the house\ncommittee Wednesday, 11. J. Berry,\nrepresenting tho Indianapolis board\nof trade, said the present marketing\nsystem was the most economical yet\ndevised and was one which gives\nthe producer the best service\n'hrough \"hedging facilities.\nRED PEPPER HEAT\nQUICKEST RELIEF\nConccntrate-d\nIlrlngs\nHeat\nQulfkes.t\nPenetrate\nIteMef.\nRheumatism, lumbago, neuritis,\nbackache, stiff neck, sore muscles,\nstrains, aching joints. Whfn you\nare suffering so you can hartlly get\naround. Just try \"Red Pepper Rub\"\nand you will have the quicken! re\nlief known.\nNothing has such concentrated,\npenetrating heat f.s red peppers. In\nstant relief. Ju.-t as soon as you ap\nply Red Pepper Rub you feel the\ntingling heat. In three minutes, it\nwarms the sore spot through and\nthrough. Frees he blood circula\ntion, breaks up the congestion\nand pain is gone.\nRowles Rod Pepper Rub made\nfrom red peppers, costs little at any\ndrug .-ttrr. Cot a jar at once. Al\nM'ist instant relief awaits you. Fso\nit for colds in chest. No matter\nwhat you have used for pain or con\ngestion, don't .'ail to try Red Pepper\nRub. A.dv.\nFROM RHEUMATISM\nt\nRELEASED ON ONE\nCHARGE; IN AGAIN\nM\na n Charged With Theft\nFrom Bread Co. i? Rear\nrested When Freed.\nFrank Marcialaski was found hot\nguilty of the charge of stealing a\nsack of flour from the South P n 1\nRr-ad Co